# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apscheduler
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Automation includes the use of various equipment and control systems such as machinery, processes in factories, boilers, and heat-treating ovens, switching on telephone networks, steering, stabilization of ships, aircraft and other applications and vehicles with reduced human intervention.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Examples range from a household thermostat controlling a boiler to a large industrial control system with tens of thousands of input measurements and output control signals.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] In the simplest type of an automatic control loop, a controller compares a measured value of a process with a desired set value and processes the resulting error signal to change some input to the process, in such a way that the process stays at its set point despite disturbances.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] This closed-loop control is an application of negative feedback to a system.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The mathematical basis of control theory began in the 18th century and advanced rapidly in the 20th.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The term *automation*, inspired by the earlier word *automatic* (coming from *automaton*), was not widely used before 1947, when Ford established an automation department.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] It was during this time that the industry was rapidly adopting feedback controllers, Technological advancements introduced in the 1930s revolutionized various industries significantly.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The World Bank's World Development Report of 2019 shows evidence that the new industries and jobs in the technology sector outweigh the economic effects of workers being displaced by automation.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Job losses and downward mobility blamed on automation have been cited as one of many factors in the resurgence of nationalist, protectionist and populist politics in the US, UK and France, among other countries since the 2010s.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] It was a preoccupation of the Greeks and Arabs (in the period between about 300 BC and about 1200 AD) to keep an accurate track of time.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] In Ptolemaic Egypt, about 270 BC, Ctesibius described a float regulator for a water clock, a device not unlike the ball and cock in a modern flush toilet.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] This was the earliest feedback-controlled mechanism.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The appearance of the mechanical clock in the 14th century made the water clock and its feedback control system obsolete.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The Persian Banū Mūsā brothers, in their *Book of Ingenious Devices* (850 AD), described a number of automatic controls.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Two-step level controls for fluids, a form of discontinuous variable structure controls, were developed by the Banu Musa brothers.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] They also described a feedback controller.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The design of feedback control systems up through the Industrial Revolution was by trial-and-error, together with a great deal of engineering intuition.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] It was not until the mid-19th century that the stability of feedback control systems was analyzed using mathematics, the formal language of automatic control theory.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was invented by Christiaan Huygens in the seventeenth century, and used to adjust the gap between millstones.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Another control mechanism was used to tent the sails of windmills.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Also in 1745, Jacques de Vaucanson invented the first automated loom.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Around 1800, Joseph Marie Jacquard created a punch-card system to program looms.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] In 1771 Richard Arkwright invented the first fully automated spinning mill driven by water power, known at the time as the water frame.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] An automatic flour mill was developed by Oliver Evans in 1785, making it the first completely automated industrial process.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Bunce of England in 1784 as part of a model steam crane.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was adopted by James Watt for use on a steam engine in 1788 after Watt's partner Boulton saw one at a flour mill Boulton & Watt were building.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The governor could not actually hold a set speed; the engine would assume a new constant speed in response to load changes.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The governor was able to handle smaller variations such as those caused by fluctuating heat load to the boiler.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Also, there was a tendency for oscillation whenever there was a speed change.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] As a consequence, engines equipped with this governor were not suitable for operations requiring constant speed, such as cotton spinning.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Several improvements to the governor, plus improvements to valve cut-off timing on the steam engine, made the engine suitable for most industrial uses before the end of the 19th century.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Advances in the steam engine stayed well ahead of science, both thermodynamics and control theory.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The governor received relatively little scientific attention until James Clerk Maxwell published a paper that established the beginning of a theoretical basis for understanding control theory.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Relay logic was introduced with factory electrification, which underwent rapid adaptation from 1900 through the 1920s.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Central electric power stations were also undergoing rapid growth and the operation of new high-pressure boilers, steam turbines and electrical substations created a great demand for instruments and controls.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Central control rooms became common in the 1920s, but as late as the early 1930s, most process controls were on-off.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Operators typically monitored charts drawn by recorders that plotted data from instruments.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] To make corrections, operators manually opened or closed valves or turned switches on or off.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Control rooms also used color-coded lights to send signals to workers in the plant to manually make certain changes.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The development of the electronic amplifier during the 1920s, which was important for long-distance telephony, required a higher signal-to-noise ratio, which was solved by negative feedback noise cancellation.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] This and other telephony applications contributed to the control theory.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] In the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flügge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic controls, which found military applications during the Second World War to fire control systems and aircraft navigation systems.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Controllers, which were able to make calculated changes in response to deviations from a set point rather than on-off control, began being introduced in the 1930s.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Controllers allowed manufacturing to continue showing productivity gains to offset the declining influence of factory electrification.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Factory productivity was greatly increased by electrification in the 1920s.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Alexander Field notes that spending on non-medical instruments increased significantly from 1929 to 1933 and remained strong thereafter.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The First and Second World Wars saw major advancements in the field of mass communication and signal processing.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Other key advances in automatic controls include differential equations, stability theory and system theory (1938), frequency domain analysis (1940), ship control (1950), and stochastic analysis (1941).
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] In 1959 Texaco's Port Arthur Refinery became the first chemical plant to use digital control.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Conversion of factories to digital control began to spread rapidly in the 1970s as the price of computer hardware fell.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The automatic telephone switchboard was introduced in 1892 along with dial telephones.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] By 1929, 31.9% of the Bell system was automatic.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Automatic telephone switching originally used vacuum tube amplifiers and electro-mechanical switches, which consumed a large amount of electricity.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Call volume eventually grew so fast that it was feared the telephone system would consume all electricity production, prompting Bell Labs to begin research on the transistor.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The logic performed by telephone switching relays was the inspiration for the digital computer.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The first commercially successful glass bottle-blowing machine was an automatic model introduced in 1905.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The machine, operated by a two-man crew working 12-hour shifts, could produce 17,280 bottles in 24 hours, compared to 2,880 bottles made by a crew of six men and boys working in a shop for a day.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The cost of making bottles by machine was 10 to 12 cents per gross compared to $1.80 per gross by the manual glassblowers and helpers.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives were developed using control theory.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives are used on different sections of a machine where a precise differential must be maintained between the sections.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] In steel rolling, the metal elongates as it passes through pairs of rollers, which must run at successively faster speeds.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] In paper making paper, the sheet shrinks as it passes around steam-heated drying arranged in groups, which must run at successively slower speeds.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The first application of a sectional electric drive was on a paper machine in 1919.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] One of the most important developments in the steel industry during the 20th century was continuous wide strip rolling, developed by Armco in 1928.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Before automation, many chemicals were made in batches.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] In 1930, with the widespread use of instruments and the emerging use of controllers, the founder of Dow Chemical Co. was advocating continuous production.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Self-acting machine tools that displaced hand dexterity so they could be operated by boys and unskilled laborers were developed by James Nasmyth in the 1840s.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Machine tools were automated with Numerical control (NC) using punched paper tape in the 1950s.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] This soon evolved into computerized numerical control (CNC).
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Today extensive automation is practiced in practically every type of manufacturing and assembly process.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Robots are especially useful in hazardous applications like automobile spray painting.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Robots are also used to assemble electronic circuit boards.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Automotive welding is done with robots and automatic welders are used in applications like pipelines.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] With the advent of the space age in 1957, controls design, particularly in the United States, turned away from the frequency-domain techniques of classical control theory and backed into the differential equation techniques of the late 19th century, which were couched in the time domain.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] During the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flugge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic control, which became widely used in hysteresis control systems such as navigation systems, fire-control systems, and electronics.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Through Flugge-Lotz and others, the modern era saw time-domain design for nonlinear systems (1961), navigation (1960), optimal control and estimation theory (1962), nonlinear control theory (1969), digital control and filtering theory (1974), and the personal computer (1983).
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Perhaps the most cited advantage of automation in industry is that it is associated with faster production and cheaper labor costs.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Another benefit could be that it replaces hard, physical, or monotonous work.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Additionally, tasks that take place in hazardous environments or that are otherwise beyond human capabilities can be done by machines, as machines can operate even under extreme temperatures or in atmospheres that are radioactive or toxic.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] They can also be maintained with simple quality checks.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] However, at the time being, not all tasks can be automated, and some tasks are more expensive to automate than others.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Initial costs of installing the machinery in factory settings are high, and failure to maintain a system could result in the loss of the product itself.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Automation primarily describes machines replacing human action, but it is also loosely associated with mechanization, machines replacing human labor.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The paradox of automation says that the more efficient the automated system, the more crucial the human contribution of the operators.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Humans are less involved, but their involvement becomes more critical.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Lisanne Bainbridge, a cognitive psychologist, identified these issues notably in her widely cited paper "Ironies of Automation." If an automated system has an error, it will multiply that error until it is fixed or shut down.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] A fatal example of this was Air France Flight 447, where a failure of automation put the pilots into a manual situation they were not prepared for.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Many roles for humans in industrial processes presently lie beyond the scope of automation.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Human-level pattern recognition, language comprehension, and language production ability are well beyond the capabilities of modern mechanical and computer systems (but see *Watson computer*).
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Tasks requiring subjective assessment or synthesis of complex sensory data, such as scents and sounds, as well as high-level tasks such as strategic planning, currently require human expertise.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] In many cases, the use of humans is more cost-effective than mechanical approaches even where the automation of industrial tasks is possible.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Therefore, algorithmic management as the digital rationalization of human labor instead of its substitution has emerged as an alternative technological strategy.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Overcoming these obstacles is a theorized path to post-scarcity economics.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] As of 2025-2026, real-world deployment of advanced robotics has revealed critical infrastructure limitations, such as "battery-life bottlenecks" (typically 2–4 hours of operation per charge) and the requirement for high-bandwidth Wi-Fi and specialized flooring for reliable function.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Additionally, robots continue to struggle with unpredictable human-made obstructions, which still necessitate human intervention to maintain operational flow.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Increased automation often causes workers to feel anxious about losing their jobs as technology renders their skills or experience unnecessary.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Early in the Industrial Revolution, when inventions like the steam engine were making some job categories expendable, workers forcefully resisted these changes.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Luddites, for instance, were English textile workers who protested the introduction of weaving machines by destroying them.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] More recently, some residents of Chandler, Arizona, have slashed tires and pelted rocks at a self-driving car, in protest over the cars' perceived threat to human safety and job prospects.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The relative anxiety about automation reflected in opinion polls seems to correlate closely with the strength of organized labor in that region or nation.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] According to one estimate, 47% of all current jobs in the US have the potential to be fully automated by 2033.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Furthermore, wages and educational attainment appear to be strongly negatively correlated with an occupation's risk of being automated.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Erik Brynjolfsson and Andrew McAfee argue that "there's never been a better time to be a worker with special skills or the right education, because these people can use technology to create and capture value.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Research by Carl Benedikt Frey and Michael Osborne of the Oxford Martin School argued that employees engaged in "tasks following well-defined procedures that can easily be performed by sophisticated algorithms" are at risk of displacement, and 47% of jobs in the US were at risk.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The study, released as a working paper in 2013 and published in 2017, predicted that automation would put low-paid physical occupations most at risk, by surveying a group of colleagues on their opinions.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] However, according to a study published in *McKinsey Quarterly* in 2015 the impact of computerization in most cases is not the replacement of employees but the automation of portions of the tasks they perform.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The methodology of the McKinsey study has been heavily criticized for being intransparent and relying on subjective assessments.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The methodology of Frey and Osborne has been subjected to criticism, as lacking evidence, historical awareness, or credible methodology.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Additionally, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) found that across the 21 OECD countries, 9% of jobs are automatable.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Based on a formula by Gilles Saint-Paul, an economist at Toulouse 1 University, the demand for unskilled human capital declines at a slower rate than the demand for skilled human capital increases.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] In the long run and for society as a whole it has led to cheaper products, lower average work hours, and new industries forming (i.e., robotics industries, computer industries, design industries).
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] These new industries provide many high salary skill-based jobs to the economy.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] By 2030, between 3 and 14 percent of the global workforce will be forced to switch job categories due to automation eliminating jobs in an entire sector.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] While the number of jobs lost to automation is often offset by jobs gained from technological advances, the same type of job loss is not the same one replaced and that leading to increasing unemployment in the lower-middle class.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] This occurs largely in the US and developed countries where technological advances contribute to higher demand for highly skilled labor but demand for middle-wage labor continues to fall.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Economists call this trend "income polarization" where unskilled labor wages are driven down and skilled labor is driven up and it is predicted to continue in developed economies.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Lights-out manufacturing is a production system with no human workers, to eliminate labor costs.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] It grew in popularity in the U.S. when General Motors in 1982 implemented humans "hands-off" manufacturing to "replace risk-averse bureaucracy with automation and robots".
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] However, the factory never reached full "lights out" status.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The costs of automation to the environment are different depending on the technology, product or engine automated.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] There are automated engines that consume more energy resources from the Earth in comparison with previous engines and vice versa.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Hazardous operations, such as oil refining, the manufacturing of industrial chemicals, and all forms of metal working, were always early contenders for automation.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The automation of vehicles could prove to have a substantial impact on the environment, although the nature of this impact could be beneficial or harmful depending on several factors.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Because automated vehicles are much less likely to get into accidents compared to human-driven vehicles, some precautions built into current models (such as anti-lock brakes or laminated glass) would not be required for self-driving versions.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Removal of these safety features reduces the weight of the vehicle, and coupled with more precise acceleration and braking, as well as fuel-efficient route mapping, can increase fuel economy and reduce emissions.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Despite this, some researchers theorize that an increase in the production of self-driving cars could lead to a boom in vehicle ownership and usage, which could potentially negate any environmental benefits of self-driving cars if they are used more frequently.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Automation of homes and home appliances is also thought to impact the environment.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] This study, along with others, indicated that the smart home's ability to monitor and adjust consumption levels would reduce unnecessary energy usage.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] However, some research suggests that smart homes might not be as efficient as non-automated homes.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] A more recent study has indicated that, while monitoring and adjusting consumption levels do decrease unnecessary energy use, this process requires monitoring systems that also consume an amount of energy.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The energy required to run these systems sometimes negates their benefits, resulting in little to no ecological benefit.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Another major shift in automation is the increased demand for flexibility and convertibility in manufacturing processes.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Manufacturers are increasingly demanding the ability to easily switch from manufacturing Product A to manufacturing Product B without having to completely rebuild the production lines.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Flexibility and distributed processes have led to the introduction of Automated Guided Vehicles with Natural Features Navigation.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Former analog-based instrumentation was replaced by digital equivalents which can be more accurate and flexible, and offer greater scope for more sophisticated configuration, parametrization, and operation.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] This was accompanied by the fieldbus revolution which provided a networked (i.e. a single cable) means of communicating between control systems and field-level instrumentation, eliminating hard-wiring.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Discrete manufacturing plants adopted these technologies fast.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The more conservative process industries with their longer plant life cycles have been slower to adopt and analog-based measurement and control still dominate.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The growing use of Industrial Ethernet on the factory floor is pushing these trends still further, enabling manufacturing plants to be integrated more tightly within the enterprise, via the internet if necessary.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Global competition has also increased demand for Reconfigurable Manufacturing Systems.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Engineers can now have numerical control over automated devices.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The result has been a rapidly expanding range of applications and human activities.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Computer-aided technologies (or CAx) now serve as the basis for mathematical and organizational tools used to create complex systems.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Notable examples of CAx include computer-aided design (CAD software) and computer-aided manufacturing (CAM software).
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The improved design, analysis, and manufacture of products enabled by CAx has been beneficial for industry.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Information technology, together with industrial machinery and processes, can assist in the design, implementation, and monitoring of control systems.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] One example of an industrial control system is a programmable logic controller (PLC).
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] PLCs are specialized hardened computers which are frequently used to synchronize the flow of inputs from (physical) sensors and events with the flow of outputs to actuators and events.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Human-machine interfaces (HMI) or computer human interfaces (CHI), formerly known as *man-machine interfaces*, are usually employed to communicate with PLCs and other computers.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Service personnel who monitor and control through HMIs can be called by different names.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] In the industrial process and manufacturing environments, they are called operators or something similar.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] In boiler houses and central utility departments, they are called *stationary engineers*.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Host simulation software (HSS) is a commonly used testing tool that is used to test the equipment software.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] HSS is used to test equipment performance concerning factory automation standards (timeouts, response time, processing time).
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Cognitive automation, as a subset of AI, is an emerging genus of automation enabled by cognitive computing.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Its primary concern is the automation of clerical tasks and workflows that consist of structuring unstructured data.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Cognitive automation relies on multiple disciplines: natural language processing, real-time computing, machine learning algorithms, big data analytics, and evidence-based learning.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Artificially intelligent computer-aided design (CAD) can use text-to-3D, image-to-3D, and video-to-3D to automate in 3D modeling.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] AI CAD libraries could also be developed using linked open data of schematics and diagrams.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Ai CAD assistants are used as tools to help streamline workflow.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Technologies like solar panels, wind turbines, and other renewable energy sources—together with smart grids, micro-grids, battery storage—can automate power production.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Many agricultural operations are automated with machinery and equipment to improve their diagnosis, decision-making and/or performing.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Agricultural automation can relieve the drudgery of agricultural work, improve the timeliness and precision of agricultural operations, raise productivity and resource-use efficiency, build resilience, and improve food quality and safety.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Increased productivity can free up labour, allowing agricultural households to spend more time elsewhere.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has resulted in progressive shifts to digital equipment and robotics.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization has generally increased in recent years.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Many supermarkets and even smaller stores are rapidly introducing self-checkout systems reducing the need for employing checkout workers.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] In the U.S., the retail industry employs 15.9 million people as of 2017 (around 1 in 9 Americans in the workforce).
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Globally, an estimated 192 million workers could be affected by automation according to research by Eurasia Group.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Online shopping could be considered a form of automated retail as the payment and checkout are through an automated online transaction processing system, with the share of online retail accounting jumping from 5.1% in 2011 to 8.3% in 2016.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] However, two-thirds of books, music, and films are now purchased online.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] In addition, automation and online shopping could reduce demands for shopping malls, and retail property, which in the United States is currently estimated to account for 31% of all commercial property or around 7 billion square feet (650 million square metres).
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Amazon has gained much of the growth in recent years for online shopping, accounting for half of the growth in online retail in 2016.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Other forms of automation can also be an integral part of online shopping, for example, the deployment of automated warehouse robotics such as that applied by Amazon using Kiva Systems.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The food retail industry has started to apply automation to the ordering process; McDonald's has introduced touch screen ordering and payment systems in many of its restaurants, reducing the need for as many cashier employees.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The University of Texas at Austin has introduced fully automated cafe retail locations.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Some cafes and restaurants have utilized mobile and tablet "apps" to make the ordering process more efficient by customers ordering and paying on their device.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Some restaurants have automated food delivery to tables of customers using a conveyor belt system.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The use of robots is sometimes employed to replace waiting staff.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Automation in construction is the combination of methods, processes, and systems that allow for greater machine autonomy in construction activities.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Construction automation may have multiple goals, including but not limited to, reducing jobsite injuries, decreasing activity completion times, and assisting with quality control and quality assurance.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Automated mining involves the removal of human labor from the mining process.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The mining industry is currently in the transition towards automation.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Currently, it can still require a large amount of human capital, particularly in the third world where labor costs are low so there is less incentive for increasing efficiency through automation.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) started the research and development of automated visual surveillance and monitoring (VSAM) program, between 1997 and 1999, and airborne video surveillance (AVS) programs, from 1998 to 2002.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Currently, there is a major effort underway in the vision community to develop a fully-automated tracking surveillance system.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Automated video surveillance monitors people and vehicles in real-time within a busy environment.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Existing automated surveillance systems are based on the environment they are primarily designed to observe, i.e., indoor, outdoor or airborne, the number of sensors that the automated system can handle and the mobility of sensors, i.e., stationary camera vs. mobile camera.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The purpose of a surveillance system is to record properties and trajectories of objects in a given area, generate warnings or notify the designated authorities in case of occurrence of particular events.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] As demands for safety and mobility have grown and technological possibilities have multiplied, interest in automation has grown.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Seeking to accelerate the development and introduction of fully automated vehicles and highways, the U.S.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Congress authorized more than $650 million over six years for intelligent transport systems (ITS) and demonstration projects in the 1991 *Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act* (ISTEA).
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Full automation commonly defined as requiring no control or very limited control by the driver; such automation would be accomplished through a combination of sensor, computer, and communications systems in vehicles and along the roadway.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Fully automated driving would, in theory, allow closer vehicle spacing and higher speeds, which could enhance traffic capacity in places where additional road building is physically impossible, politically unacceptable, or prohibitively expensive.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Automated controls also might enhance road safety by reducing the opportunity for driver error, which causes a large share of motor vehicle crashes.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Other potential benefits include improved air quality (as a result of more-efficient traffic flows), increased fuel economy, and spin-off technologies generated during research and development related to automated highway systems.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Automated waste collection trucks prevent the need for as many workers as well as easing the level of labor required to provide the service.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Business process automation (BPA) is the technology-enabled automation of complex business processes.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] It can help to streamline a business for simplicity, achieve digital transformation, increase service quality, improve service delivery or contain costs.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] BPA consists of integrating applications, restructuring labor resources and using software applications throughout the organization.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Robotic process automation (RPA; or RPAAI for self-guided RPA 2.0) is an emerging field within BPA and uses AI.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] BPAs can be implemented in a number of business areas including recruitment, marketing, sales and workflow.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Home automation (also called **domotics**) designates an emerging practice of increased automation of household appliances and features in residential dwellings, particularly through electronic means that allow for things impracticable, overly expensive or simply not possible in recent past decades.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The rise in the usage of home automation solutions has taken a turn reflecting the increased dependency of people on such automation solutions.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] However, the increased comfort that gets added through these automation solutions is remarkable.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Automation is essential for many scientific and clinical applications.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Therefore, automation has been extensively employed in laboratories.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] From as early as 1980 fully automated laboratories have already been working.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] However, automation has not become widespread in laboratories due to its high cost.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] This may change with the ability of integrating low-cost devices with standard laboratory equipment.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Autosamplers are common devices used in laboratory automation.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Logistics automation is the application of computer software or automated machinery to improve the efficiency of logistics operations.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Typically this refers to operations within a warehouse or distribution center, with broader tasks undertaken by supply chain engineering systems and enterprise resource planning systems.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Industrial automation deals primarily with the automation of manufacturing, quality control, and material handling processes.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] General-purpose controllers for industrial processes include programmable logic controllers, stand-alone I/O modules, and computers.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Industrial automation is to replace the human action and manual command-response activities with the use of mechanized equipment and logical programming commands.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] One trend is increased use of machine vision to provide automatic inspection and robot guidance functions, another is a continuing increase in the use of robots.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Industrial automation is simply required in industries.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The rise of industrial automation is directly tied to the "Fourth Industrial Revolution", which is better known now as Industry 4.0.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Originating from Germany, Industry 4.0 encompasses numerous devices, concepts, and machines, as well as the advancement of the industrial internet of things (IIoT).
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] An "Internet of Things is a seamless integration of diverse physical objects in the Internet through a virtual representation".
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] These new advancements have drawn attention to the world of automation and have shown ways for it to increase productivity and efficiency in machinery and manufacturing facilities.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 works with the IIoT and software/hardware to connect in a way that (through communication technologies) add enhancements and improve manufacturing processes.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Being able to create more advanced manufacturing is now possible with these new technologies.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] It opens up an improved manufacturing platform.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Implementation of systems such as SCADA is an example of software that takes place in industrial automation today.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] SCADA is a supervisory data collection software, just one of the many used in industrial automation.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 covers many areas in manufacturing.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Industrial robotics is a sub-branch in industrial automation that aids in various manufacturing processes.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Such manufacturing processes include machining, welding, painting, assembling and material handling to name a few.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Industrial robots use various mechanical, electrical as well as software systems to allow for high precision, accuracy and speed that far exceed any human performance.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The birth of industrial robots came shortly after World War II as the U.S. saw the need for a quicker way to produce industrial and consumer goods.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Servos, digital logic and solid-state electronics allowed engineers to build better and faster systems and over time these systems were improved and revised to the point where a single robot is capable of running 24 hours a day with little or no maintenance.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] In 1997, there were 700,000 industrial robots in use, the number has risen to 1.8M in 2017 In recent years, AI with robotics is also used in creating an automatic labeling solution, using robotic arms as the automatic label applicator, and AI for learning and detecting the products to be labelled.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Industrial automation incorporates programmable logic controllers in the manufacturing process.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) use a processing system which allows for variation of controls of inputs and outputs using simple programming.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] PLCs make use of programmable memory, storing instructions and functions like logic, sequencing, timing, counting, etc.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Using a logic-based language, a PLC can receive a variety of inputs and return a variety of logical outputs, the input devices being sensors and output devices being motors, valves, etc.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] PLCs are similar to computers, however, while computers are optimized for calculations, PLCs are optimized for control tasks and use in industrial environments.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] They are built so that only basic logic-based programming knowledge is needed and to handle vibrations, high temperatures, humidity, and noise.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The greatest advantage PLCs offer is their flexibility.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] With the same basic controllers, a PLC can operate a range of different control systems.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] PLCs make it unnecessary to rewire a system to change the control system.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] This flexibility leads to a cost-effective system for complex and varied control systems.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] PLCs can range from small "building brick" devices with tens of I/O in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs (I/O), extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] It was from the automotive industry in the United States that the PLC was born.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Before the PLC, control, sequencing, and safety interlock logic for manufacturing automobiles was mainly composed of relays, cam timers, drum sequencers, and dedicated closed-loop controllers.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Since these could number in the hundreds or even thousands, the process for updating such facilities for the yearly model change-over was very time-consuming and expensive, as electricians needed to individually rewire the relays to change their operational characteristics.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] When digital computers became available, being general-purpose programmable devices, they were soon applied to control sequential and combinatorial logic in industrial processes.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] However, these early computers required specialist programmers and stringent operating environmental control for temperature, cleanliness, and power quality.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] To meet these challenges, the PLC was developed with several key attributes.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] It would tolerate the shop-floor environment, it would support discrete (bit-form) input and output in an easily extensible manner, it would not require years of training to use, and it would permit its operation to be monitored.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Since many industrial processes have timescales easily addressed by millisecond response times, modern (fast, small, reliable) electronics greatly facilitate building reliable controllers, and performance could be traded off for reliability.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Agent-assisted automation refers to automation used by call center agents to handle customer inquiries.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The key benefit of agent-assisted automation is compliance and error-proofing.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] Agents are sometimes not fully trained or they forget or ignore key steps in the process.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] The use of automation ensures that what is supposed to happen on the call actually does, every time.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p01] There are two basic types: desktop automation and automated voice solutions.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] One of the simplest types of control is *on-off* control.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] An example is a thermostat used on household appliances which either open or close an electrical contact.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] Sequence control, in which a programmed sequence of *discrete* operations is performed, often based on system logic that involves system states.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] An elevator control system is an example of sequence control.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] A proportional–integral–derivative controller (PID controller) is a control loop feedback mechanism (controller) widely used in industrial control systems.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] The theoretical understanding and application date from the 1920s, and they are implemented in nearly all analog control systems; originally in mechanical controllers, and then using discrete electronics and latterly in industrial process computers.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] Sequential control may be either to a fixed sequence or to a logical one that will perform different actions depending on various system states.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] An example of an adjustable but otherwise fixed sequence is a timer on a lawn sprinkler.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] States refer to the various conditions that can occur in a use or sequence scenario of the system.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] An example is an elevator, which uses logic based on the system state to perform certain actions in response to its state and operator input.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] For example, if the operator presses the floor n button, the system will respond depending on whether the elevator is stopped or moving, going up or down, or if the door is open or closed, and other conditions.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] Early development of sequential control was relay logic, by which electrical relays engage electrical contacts which either start or interrupt power to a device.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] Relays were first used in telegraph networks before being developed for controlling other devices, such as when starting and stopping industrial-sized electric motors or opening and closing solenoid valves.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] Using relays for control purposes allowed event-driven control, where actions could be triggered out of sequence, in response to external events.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] These were more flexible in their response than the rigid single-sequence cam timers.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] More complicated examples involved maintaining safe sequences for devices such as swing bridge controls, where a lock bolt needed to be disengaged before the bridge could be moved, and the lock bolt could not be released until the safety gates had already been closed.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] The total number of relays and cam timers can number into the hundreds or even thousands in some factories.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] Early programming techniques and languages were needed to make such systems manageable, one of the first being ladder logic, where diagrams of the interconnected relays resembled the rungs of a ladder.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] Special computers called programmable logic controllers were later designed to replace these collections of hardware with a single, more easily re-programmed unit.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] In a typical hard-wired motor start and stop circuit (called a *control circuit*) a motor is started by pushing a "Start" or "Run" button that activates a pair of electrical relays.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] The "lock-in" relay locks in contacts that keep the control circuit energized when the push-button is released.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] (The start button is a normally open contact and the stop button is a normally closed contact.) Another relay energizes a switch that powers the device that throws the motor starter switch (three sets of contacts for three-phase industrial power) in the main power circuit.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] Large motors use high voltage and experience high in-rush current, making speed important in making and breaking contact.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] This can be dangerous for personnel and property with manual switches.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] The "lock-in" contacts in the start circuit and the main power contacts for the motor are held engaged by their respective electromagnets until a "stop" or "off" button is pressed, which de-energizes the lock in relay.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] Commonly interlocks are added to a control circuit.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] Suppose that the motor in the example is powering machinery that has a critical need for lubrication.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] In this case, an interlock could be added to ensure that the oil pump is running before the motor starts.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] Timers, limit switches, and electric eyes are other common elements in control circuits.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] Solenoid valves are widely used on compressed air or hydraulic fluid for powering actuators on mechanical components.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] Computers can perform both sequential control and feedback control, and typically a single computer will do both in an industrial application.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) are a type of special-purpose microprocessor that replaced many hardware components such as timers and drum sequencers used in relay logic–type systems.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] General-purpose process control computers have increasingly replaced stand-alone controllers, with a single computer able to perform the operations of hundreds of controllers.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] Process control computers can process data from a network of PLCs, instruments, and controllers to implement typical (such as PID) control of many individual variables or, in some cases, to implement complex control algorithms using multiple inputs and mathematical manipulations.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] They can also analyze data and create real-time graphical displays for operators and run reports for operators, engineers, and management.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] Control of an automated teller machine (ATM) is an example of an interactive process in which a computer will perform a logic-derived response to a user selection based on information retrieved from a networked database.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] The ATM process has similarities with other online transaction processes.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] The different logical responses are called *scenarios*.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] Such processes are typically designed with the aid of use cases and flowcharts, which guide the writing of the software code.
[src:apscheduler/automation-p02] The earliest feedback control mechanism was the water clock invented by Greek engineer Ctesibius (285–222 BC).
[src:apscheduler/cron] The daemon name originates from Chronos, the Greek word for time.
[src:apscheduler/cron] `cron` is generally available on Unix-like operating systems.
[src:apscheduler/cron] The actions of cron are driven by a *crontab* (cron table) file.
[src:apscheduler/cron] The crontab files are stored where the lists of jobs and other instructions to the cron daemon are kept.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Users can have their own individual crontab files and often there is a system-wide crontab file (usually in `/etc` or a subdirectory of `/etc` e.g.
[src:apscheduler/cron] `/etc/cron.d`) that only system administrators can edit.
[src:apscheduler/cron] The syntax of each line expects a cron expression made of five fields which represent the time to execute the command, followed by a shell command to execute.
[src:apscheduler/cron] While normally the job is executed when the time/date specification fields all match the current time and date, there is one exception: if both "day of month" (field 3) and "day of week" (field 5) are restricted (do not contain "*"), then one or both must match the current day.
[src:apscheduler/cron] This example runs a shell program called export_dump.sh at 23:45 (11:45 PM) every Saturday.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Note: On some systems it is also possible to specify `*/n` to run for every *n*-th interval of time.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Also, specifying multiple specific time intervals can be done with commas (e.g., `1,2,3`).
[src:apscheduler/cron] The line below would output "hello world" to the command line every 5th minute of every first, second and third hour (i.e., 01:00, 01:05, 01:10, up until 03:55).
[src:apscheduler/cron] The configuration file for a user can be edited by calling `crontab -e` regardless of where the actual implementation stores this file.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Some `cron` implementations, such as the popular 4th BSD edition written by Paul Vixie and included in many Linux distributions, add a sixth field: an account username that runs the specified job (subject to user existence and permissions).
[src:apscheduler/cron] This is allowed only in the system crontabs—not in others, which are each assigned to a single user to configure.
[src:apscheduler/cron] The sixth field is alternatively sometimes used for *year* instead of an account username—the nncron daemon for Windows does this.
[src:apscheduler/cron] The Amazon EventBridge implementation of cron does not use 0 based day of week, instead it is 1-7 SUN-SAT (instead of 0-6), as well as supporting additional expression features such as first-weekday and last-day-of-month.
[src:apscheduler/cron] `@reboot` configures a job to run once when the daemon is started.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Since cron is typically never restarted, this typically corresponds to the machine being booted.
[src:apscheduler/cron] This behavior is enforced in some variations of cron, such as that provided in Debian, so that simply restarting the daemon does not re-run `@reboot` jobs.
[src:apscheduler/cron] `@reboot` can be useful if there is a need to start up a server or daemon under a particular user, and the user does not have access to configure init to start the program.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Note that if neither of these files exists then, depending on site-dependent configuration parameters, either only the super user can use cron jobs, or all users can use cron jobs.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Most cron implementations simply interpret crontab entries in the system time zone setting that the cron daemon runs under.
[src:apscheduler/cron] This can be a source of dispute if a large multi-user machine has users in several time zones, especially if the system default time zone includes the potentially confusing DST.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Thus, a cron implementation may as a special case recognize lines of the form "CRON_TZ=<time zone>" in user crontabs, interpreting subsequent crontab entries relative to that time zone.
[src:apscheduler/cron] The cron in Version 7 Unix was a system service (later called a daemon) invoked from `/etc/rc` when the operating system entered multi-user mode.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Determine if any commands must run at the current date and time, and if so, run them as the superuser, root.
[src:apscheduler/cron] This version of cron was basic and robust but it also consumed resources whether it found any work to do or not.
[src:apscheduler/cron] In an experiment at Purdue University in the late 1970s to extend cron's service to all 100 users on a time-shared VAX, it was found to place too much load on the system.
[src:apscheduler/cron] The next version of cron, with the release of Unix System V, was created to extend the capabilities of cron to all users of a Unix system, not just the superuser.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Though this may seem trivial today with most Unix and Unix-like systems having powerful processors and small numbers of users, at the time it required a new approach on a one-MIPS system having roughly 100 user accounts.
[src:apscheduler/cron] In the August, 1977 issue of the *Communications of the ACM*, W.
[src:apscheduler/cron] A Purdue graduate student, Robert Brown, reviewing this article, recognized the parallel between cron and discrete event simulators, and created an implementation of the Franta–Maly event list manager (ELM) for experimentation.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Discrete event simulators run in *virtual time*, peeling events off the event queue as quickly as possible and advancing their notion of "now" to the scheduled time of the next event.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Running the event simulator in "real time" instead of virtual time created a version of cron that spent most of its time sleeping, waiting for the scheduled time to execute the task at the head of the event list.
[src:apscheduler/cron] The following school year brought new students into the graduate program at Purdue, including Keith Williamson, who joined the systems staff in the Computer Science department.
[src:apscheduler/cron] As a "warm up task" Brown asked him to flesh out the prototype cron into a production service, and this multi-user cron went into use at Purdue in late 1979.
[src:apscheduler/cron] This version of cron wholly replaced the `/etc/cron` that was in use on the computer science department's VAX 11/780 running 32/V.
[src:apscheduler/cron] For each crontab file found, determine the next time in the future that each command must run.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Place those commands on the Franta–Maly event list with their corresponding time and their "five field" time specifier.
[src:apscheduler/cron] On awakening and after verifying the correct time, execute the task at the head of the queue (in background) with the privileges of the user who created it.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Determine the next time in the future to run this command and place it back on the event list at that time value.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Additionally, the daemon responds to SIGHUP signals to rescan modified crontab files and schedules special "wake up events" on the hour and half-hour to look for modified crontab files.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Much detail is omitted here concerning the inaccuracies of computer time-of-day tracking, Unix alarm scheduling, explicit time-of-day changes, and process management, all of which account for the majority of the lines of code in this cron.
[src:apscheduler/cron] This cron also captured the output of *stdout* and *stderr* and e-mailed any output to the crontab owner.
[src:apscheduler/cron] The resources consumed by this cron scale only with the amount of work it is given and do not inherently increase over time, with the exception of periodically checking for changes.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Williamson completed his studies and departed the University with a Masters of Science in Computer Science and joined AT&T Bell Labs in Murray Hill, New Jersey, and took this cron with him.
[src:apscheduler/cron] This version of cron later appeared largely unchanged in Unix System V and in BSD and their derivatives, Solaris from Sun Microsystems, IRIX from Silicon Graphics, HP-UX from Hewlett-Packard, and AIX from IBM.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Technically, the original license for these implementations should be with the Purdue Research Foundation who funded the work, but this took place at a time when little concern was given to such matters.
[src:apscheduler/cron] With the advent of the GNU Project and Linux, new crons appeared.
[src:apscheduler/cron] The most prevalent of these is the Vixie cron, originally coded by Paul Vixie in 1987.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Version 3 of **Vixie cron** was released in late 1993.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Version 4.1 was renamed to **ISC Cron** and was released in January 2004.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Version 3, with some minor bugfixes, is used in most distributions of Linux and BSDs.
[src:apscheduler/cron] In 2007, Red Hat forked vixie-cron 4.1 to the cronie project, adding features such as PAM and SELinux support.
[src:apscheduler/cron] In 2009, anacron 2.3 was merged into cronie.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Anacron is not an independent cron program however; another cron job must call it.
[src:apscheduler/cron] DragonFly's dcron was made by its founder Matt Dillon, and its maintainership was taken over by Jim Pryor in 2010.
[src:apscheduler/cron] In 2003, Dale Mellor introduced mcron, a cron variant written in Guile which provides cross-compatibility with Vixie cron while also providing greater flexibility as it allows arbitrary scheme code to be used in scheduling calculations and job definitions.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Since both the mcron daemon and the crontab files are usually written in scheme (though mcron also accepts traditional Vixie crontabs), the cumulative state of a user's job queue is available to their job code, which may be scheduled to run iff the results of other jobs meet certain criteria.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Mcron is deployed by default under the Guix package manager, which includes provisions (services) for the package manager to monadically emit mcron crontabs while both ensuring that packages needed for job execution are installed and that the corresponding crontabs correctly refer to them.
[src:apscheduler/cron] A webcron solution schedules ring tasks to run on a regular basis wherever cron implementations are not available in a web hosting environment.
[src:apscheduler/cron] In 2025, the Open Cron Pattern Specification (OCPS) was published to address fragmentation in cron syntax across different implementations.
[src:apscheduler/cron] OCPS 1.0 provides a formal specification of the Vixie cron dialect, codifying the five-field pattern format with explicit rules for previously ambiguous edge cases.
[src:apscheduler/cron] The specification is designed as a backward-compatible superset, with future versions planned to incrementally add features such as predefined schedules, second-level precision, and advanced calendar modifiers while maintaining compatibility with earlier versions.
[src:apscheduler/cron] A cron expression is a string comprising five, six, or seven fields separated by white space that represents a set of times, normally as a schedule to execute some routine.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Comments begin with a comment mark #, and must be on a line by themselves.
[src:apscheduler/cron] The month and weekday abbreviations are not case-sensitive.
[src:apscheduler/cron] In the particular case of the system crontab file (/etc/crontab), a *user* field inserts itself before the *command*.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Asterisks (also known as wildcard) represents "all".
[src:apscheduler/cron] For example, using "* * * * *" will run every minute.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Using "* * * * 1" will run every minute only on Monday.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Using six asterisks means every second when seconds are supported.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Commas are used to separate items of a list.
[src:apscheduler/cron] For example, using "MON,WED,FRI" in the 5th field (day of week) means Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays.
[src:apscheduler/cron] For example, "2000-2010" indicates every year between 2000 and 2010, inclusive.
[src:apscheduler/cron] % are sent to the command as standard input.
[src:apscheduler/cron] The following are non-standard characters and exist only in some cron implementations, such as the Quartz Java scheduler.
[src:apscheduler/cron] In the day-of-month field, it specifies the last day of the month.
[src:apscheduler/cron] The 'W' character is allowed for the day-of-month field.
[src:apscheduler/cron] This character is used to specify the weekday (Monday-Friday) nearest the given day.
[src:apscheduler/cron] " is specified as the value for the day-of-month field, the meaning is: "the nearest weekday to the 15th of the month." So, if the 15th is a Saturday, the trigger fires on Friday the 14th.
[src:apscheduler/cron] If the 15th is a Sunday, the trigger fires on Monday the 16th.
[src:apscheduler/cron] If the 15th is a Tuesday, then it fires on Tuesday the 15th.
[src:apscheduler/cron] However, if "1W" is specified as the value for day-of-month, and the 1st is a Saturday, the trigger fires on Monday the 3rd, as it does not 'jump' over the boundary of a month's days.
[src:apscheduler/cron] The 'W' character can be specified only when the day-of-month is a single day, not a range or list of days.
[src:apscheduler/cron] '#' is allowed for the day-of-week field, and must be followed by a number between one and five.
[src:apscheduler/cron] It allows specifying constructs such as "the second Friday" of a given month.
[src:apscheduler/cron] For example, entering "5#3" in the day-of-week field corresponds to the third Friday of every month.
[src:apscheduler/cron] ' for leaving either day-of-month or day-of-week blank.
[src:apscheduler/cron] if cron started-up on 8:25am, and would run at this time every day until restarted again.
[src:apscheduler/cron] In vixie-cron, slashes can be combined with ranges to specify step values.
[src:apscheduler/cron] in the minutes field indicates every 5 minutes (see note below about frequencies).
[src:apscheduler/cron] POSIX does not define a use for slashes; its rationale (commenting on a BSD extension) notes that the definition is based on System V format but does not exclude the possibility of extensions.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Some language-specific libraries offering crontab scheduling ability do not require "strict" ranges 15-59/XX to the left of the slash when ranges are used.
[src:apscheduler/cron] In these cases, 15/XX is the same as a vixie-cron schedule of 15-59/10 in the minutes section.
[src:apscheduler/cron] Similarly, one can remove the extra -23 from 0-23/XX, -31 from 1-31/XX, and -12 from 1-12/XX for hours, days, and months; respectively.
[src:apscheduler/cron] continuous integration system to indicate that a "hashed" value is substituted.
[src:apscheduler/cron] ' indicates that the task is performed every hour at an unspecified but invariant time for each task.
[src:apscheduler/cron] This allows spreading out tasks over time, rather than having all of them start at the same time and compete for resources.
[src:apscheduler/job-scheduler] A **job scheduler** is a computer application for controlling unattended background program execution of jobs.
[src:apscheduler/job-scheduler] This is commonly called **batch scheduling**, as execution of non-interactive jobs is often called batch processing, though traditional *job* and *batch* are distinguished and contrasted; see that page for details.
[src:apscheduler/job-scheduler] Other synonyms include **batch system**, **distributed resource management system** (**DRMS**), **distributed resource manager** (**DRM**), and, commonly today, **workload automation** (**WLA**).
[src:apscheduler/job-scheduler] The data structure of jobs to run is known as the job queue.
[src:apscheduler/job-scheduler] Modern job schedulers typically provide a graphical user interface and a single point of control for definition and monitoring of background executions in a distributed network of computers.
[src:apscheduler/job-scheduler] Increasingly, job schedulers are required to orchestrate the integration of real-time business activities with traditional background IT processing across different operating system platforms and business application environments.
[src:apscheduler/job-scheduler] If software from a completely different area includes all or some of those features, this software can be considered to have job scheduling capabilities.
[src:apscheduler/job-scheduler] Most operating systems, such as Unix and Windows, provide basic job scheduling capabilities, notably by at and batch, cron, and the Windows Task Scheduler.
[src:apscheduler/job-scheduler] Web hosting services provide job scheduling capabilities through a control panel or a webcron solution.
[src:apscheduler/job-scheduler] Many programs such as DBMS, backup, ERPs, and BPM also include relevant job-scheduling capabilities.
[src:apscheduler/job-scheduler] Operating system ("OS") or point program supplied job-scheduling will not usually provide the ability to schedule beyond a single OS instance or outside the remit of the specific program.
[src:apscheduler/job-scheduler] These advanced capabilities can be written by in-house developers but are more often provided by suppliers who specialize in systems-management software.
[src:apscheduler/job-scheduler] There are many concepts that are central to almost every job scheduler implementation and that are widely recognized with minimal variations: jobs, dependencies, job streams, and users.
[src:apscheduler/job-scheduler] Beyond the basic, single OS instance scheduling tools there are two major architectures that exist for Job Scheduling software.
[src:apscheduler/job-scheduler] Job schedulers have been one of the major components of IT infrastructure since the early mainframe systems.
[src:apscheduler/job-scheduler] At first, stacks of punched cards were processed one after the other, hence the term "batch processing".
[src:apscheduler/job-scheduler] Various schemes are used to decide which particular job to run.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In computing, **scheduling** is the action of assigning resources to perform tasks.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The resources may be processors, network links or expansion cards.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The tasks may be threads, processes or data flows.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The scheduling activity is carried out by a mechanism called a **scheduler**.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Schedulers are often designed so as to keep all computer resources busy (as in load balancing), allow multiple users to share system resources effectively, or to achieve a target quality-of-service.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Scheduling is fundamental to computation itself, and an intrinsic part of the execution model of a computer system; the concept of scheduling makes it possible to have computer multitasking with a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In practice, these goals often conflict (e.g. throughput versus latency), thus a scheduler will implement a suitable compromise.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Preference is measured by any one of the concerns mentioned above, depending upon the user's needs and objectives.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In real-time environments, such as embedded systems for automatic control in industry (for example robotics), the scheduler also must ensure that processes can meet deadlines; this is crucial for keeping the system stable.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Scheduled tasks can also be distributed to remote devices across a network and managed through an administrative back end.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The scheduler is an operating system module that selects the next jobs to be admitted into the system and the next process to run.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Operating systems may feature up to three distinct scheduler types: a *long-term scheduler* (also known as an admission scheduler or high-level scheduler), a *mid-term or medium-term scheduler*, and a *short-term scheduler*.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The names suggest the relative frequency with which their functions are performed.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The process scheduler is a part of the operating system that decides which process runs at a certain point in time.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] It usually has the ability to pause a running process, move it to the back of the running queue and start a new process; such a scheduler is known as a *preemptive scheduler*.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] If the scheduler cannot pause a running process and start a new process, the scheduler is a *cooperative scheduler*.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] We distinguish between *long-term scheduling*, *medium-term scheduling*, and *short-term scheduling* based on how often decisions must be made.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Thus, this scheduler dictates what processes are to run on a system, the degree of concurrency to be supported at any one time – whether many or few processes are to be executed concurrently, and how the split between I/O-intensive and CPU-intensive processes is to be handled.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The long-term scheduler is responsible for controlling the degree of multiprogramming.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In general, most processes can be described as either I/O-bound or CPU-bound.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] An I/O-bound process is one that spends more of its time doing I/O than it spends doing computations.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] A CPU-bound process, in contrast, generates I/O requests infrequently, using more of its time doing computations.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] It is important that a long-term scheduler selects a good process mix of I/O-bound and CPU-bound processes.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] If all processes are I/O-bound, the ready queue will almost always be empty, and the short-term scheduler will have little to do.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] On the other hand, if all processes are CPU-bound, the I/O waiting queue will almost always be empty, devices will go unused, and again the system will be unbalanced.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The system with the best performance will thus have a combination of CPU-bound and I/O-bound processes.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In modern operating systems, this is used to make sure that real-time processes get enough CPU time to finish their tasks.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Long-term scheduling is also important in large-scale systems such as batch processing systems, computer clusters, supercomputers, and render farms.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] For example, in concurrent systems, coscheduling of interacting processes is often required to prevent them from blocking due to waiting on each other.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In these cases, special-purpose job scheduler software is typically used to assist these functions, in addition to any underlying admission scheduling support in the operating system.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Some operating systems only allow new tasks to be added if it is sure all real-time deadlines can still be met.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The specific heuristic algorithm used by an operating system to accept or reject new tasks is the *admission control mechanism*.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The *medium-term scheduler* temporarily removes processes from main memory and places them in secondary memory (such as a hard disk drive) or vice versa, which is commonly referred to as *swapping out* or *swapping in* (also incorrectly as *paging out* or *paging in*).
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In many systems today (those that support mapping virtual address space to secondary storage other than the swap file), the medium-term scheduler may actually perform the role of the long-term scheduler, by treating binaries as *swapped-out processes* upon their execution.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In this way, when a segment of the binary is required, it can be swapped in on demand, or *lazy loaded*, also called demand paging.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The *short-term scheduler* (also known as the *CPU scheduler*) decides which of the ready, in-memory processes is to be executed (allocated a CPU) after a clock interrupt, an I/O interrupt, an operating system call or another form of signal.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Thus, the short-term scheduler makes scheduling decisions much more frequently than the long-term or mid-term schedulers – A scheduling decision will, at a minimum, have to be made after every time slice, and these are very short.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] This scheduler can be preemptive, implying that it is capable of forcibly removing processes from a CPU when it decides to allocate that CPU to another process, or non-preemptive (also known as *voluntary* or *co-operative*), in which case the scheduler is unable to *force* processes off the CPU.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Another component that is involved in the CPU-scheduling function is the dispatcher, which is the module that gives control of the CPU to the process selected by the short-term scheduler.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] It receives control in kernel mode as the result of an interrupt or system call.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The dispatcher should be as fast as possible since it is invoked during every process switch.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] During the context switches, the processor is virtually idle for a fraction of time, thus unnecessary context switches should be avoided.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The time it takes for the dispatcher to stop one process and start another is known as the *dispatch latency*.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] A **scheduling discipline** (also called **scheduling policy** or **scheduling algorithm**) is an algorithm used for distributing resources among parties that simultaneously and asynchronously request them.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Scheduling disciplines are used in routers (to handle packet traffic) as well as in operating systems (to share CPU time among both threads and processes), disk drives (I/O scheduling), printers (print spooler), most embedded systems, etc.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The main purposes of scheduling algorithms are to minimize resource starvation and to ensure fairness amongst the parties utilizing the resources.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Scheduling deals with the problem of deciding which of the outstanding requests is to be allocated resources.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] There are many different scheduling algorithms.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In this section, we introduce several of them.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In packet-switched computer networks and other statistical multiplexing, the notion of a **scheduling algorithm** is used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing of data packets.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The simplest best-effort scheduling algorithms are round-robin, fair queuing (a max-min fair scheduling algorithm), proportional-fair scheduling and maximum throughput.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] If differentiated or guaranteed quality of service is offered, as opposed to best-effort communication, weighted fair queuing may be utilized.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In advanced packet radio wireless networks such as HSDPA (High-Speed Downlink Packet Access) 3.5G cellular system, **channel-dependent scheduling** may be used to take advantage of channel state information.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] If the channel conditions are favourable, the throughput and system spectral efficiency may be increased.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In even more advanced systems such as LTE, the scheduling is combined by channel-dependent packet-by-packet dynamic channel allocation, or by assigning OFDMA multi-carriers or other frequency-domain equalization components to the users that best can utilize them.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Earliest deadline first (EDF) or *least time to go* is a dynamic scheduling algorithm used in real-time operating systems to place processes in a priority queue.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Whenever a scheduling event occurs (a task finishes, a new task is released, etc.), the queue will be searched for the process closest to its deadline, which will be the next to be scheduled for execution.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] With this strategy the scheduler arranges processes with the least estimated processing time remaining to be next in the queue.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] This requires advanced knowledge or estimations about the time required for a process to complete.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The operating system assigns a fixed-priority rank to every process, and the scheduler arranges the processes in the ready queue in order of their priority.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Lower-priority processes get interrupted by incoming higher-priority processes.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The scheduler assigns a fixed time unit per process, and cycles through them.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] If the process completes within that time slice, it gets terminated otherwise, it is rescheduled after giving a chance to all other processes.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] This is used for situations in which processes are easily divided into different groups.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] For example, a common division is made between foreground (interactive) processes and background (batch) processes.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] These two types of processes have different response-time requirements and so may have different scheduling needs.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] It is very useful for shared memory problems.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] A work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that always tries to keep the scheduled resources busy if there are submitted jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In contrast, a non-work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that, in some cases, may leave the scheduled resources idle despite the presence of jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] A very common method in embedded systems is to schedule jobs manually.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] This can, for example, be done in a time-multiplexed fashion.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Sometimes the kernel is divided in three or more parts: Manual scheduling, preemptive and interrupt level.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Exact methods for scheduling jobs are often proprietary.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] When designing an operating system, a programmer must consider which scheduling algorithm will perform best for the use the system is going to see.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] There is no universal *best* scheduling algorithm, and many operating systems use extended or combinations of the scheduling algorithms above.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] For example, Windows NT/XP/Vista uses a multilevel feedback queue, a combination of fixed-priority preemptive scheduling, round-robin, and first-in, first-out algorithms.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In this system, threads can dynamically increase or decrease in priority depending on if it has been serviced already or if it has been waiting extensively.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Every priority level is represented by its own queue, with round-robin scheduling among the high-priority threads and FIFO among the lower-priority ones.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In this sense, response time is short for most threads, and short but critical system threads get completed very quickly.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Since threads can only use one time unit of the round-robin in the highest-priority queue, starvation can be a problem for longer high-priority threads.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The algorithm used may be as simple as round-robin in which each process is given equal time (for instance, 1 ms, usually between 1 ms and 100 ms) in a cycling list.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] So, process A executes for 1 ms, then process B, then process C, then back to process A.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] More advanced algorithms take into account process priority, or the importance of the process.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] This allows some processes to use more time than others.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The kernel always uses whatever resources it needs to ensure proper functioning of the system, and so can be said to have infinite priority.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In SMP systems, processor affinity is considered to increase overall system performance, even if it may cause a process itself to run more slowly.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] This generally improves performance by reducing cache thrashing.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] IBM OS/360 was available with three different schedulers.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Later virtual storage versions of MVS added a *Workload Manager* feature to the scheduler, which schedules processor resources according to an elaborate scheme defined by the installation.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Very early MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows systems were non-multitasking, and as such did not feature a scheduler.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Windows 3.1x used a non-preemptive scheduler, meaning that it did not interrupt programs.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] It relied on the program to end or tell the OS that it didn't need the processor so that it could move on to another process.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] This is usually called cooperative multitasking.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Windows 95 introduced a rudimentary preemptive scheduler; however, for legacy support opted to let 16-bit applications run without preemption.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Windows NT-based operating systems use a multilevel feedback queue.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] 32 priority levels are defined, 0 through 31, with priorities 0 through 15 being *normal* priorities and priorities 16 through 31 being soft real-time priorities, requiring privileges to assign.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] User interfaces and APIs work with priority classes for the process and the threads in the process, which are then combined by the system into the absolute priority level.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The scheduler was modified in Windows Vista to use the cycle counter register of modern processors to keep track of exactly how many CPU cycles a thread has executed, rather than just using an interval-timer interrupt routine.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Vista also uses a priority scheduler for the I/O queue so that disk defragmenters and other such programs do not interfere with foreground operations.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Mac OS 9 uses cooperative scheduling for threads, where one process controls multiple cooperative threads, and also provides preemptive scheduling for multiprocessing tasks.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The kernel schedules multiprocessing tasks using a preemptive scheduling algorithm.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] All Process Manager processes run within a special multiprocessing task, called the *blue task*.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Those processes are scheduled cooperatively, using a round-robin scheduling algorithm; a process yields control of the processor to another process by explicitly calling a blocking function such as `WaitNextEvent`.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Each process has its own copy of the Thread Manager that schedules that process's threads cooperatively; a thread yields control of the processor to another thread by calling `YieldToAnyThread` or `YieldToThread`.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] macOS uses a multilevel feedback queue, with four priority bands for threads – normal, system high priority, kernel mode only, and real-time.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Threads are scheduled preemptively; macOS also supports cooperatively scheduled threads in its implementation of the Thread Manager in Carbon.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Threads are primarily of interest for applications that currently consist of several asynchronous processes.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] These applications might impose a lighter load on the system if converted to a multithreaded structure.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] AIX 5 implements the following scheduling policies: FIFO, round robin, and fair round robin.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The FIFO policy has three different implementations: FIFO, FIFO2, and FIFO3.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The round robin policy is named SCHED_RR in AIX, and the fair round robin is called SCHED_OTHER.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Linux 1.2 used a round-robin scheduling policy.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Linux 2.2 added scheduling classes and support for symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In Linux 2.4, an O(n) scheduler with a multilevel feedback queue with priority levels ranging from 0 to 140 was used; 0–99 are reserved for real-time tasks and 100–140 are considered nice task levels.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] For real-time tasks, the time quantum for switching processes was approximately 200 ms, and for nice tasks approximately 10 ms.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The scheduler ran through the run queue of all ready processes, letting the highest priority processes go first and run through their time slices, after which they will be placed in an expired queue.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] When the active queue is empty, the expired queue will become the active queue and vice versa.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] However, some enterprise Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux Enterprise Server replaced this scheduler with a backport of the O(1) scheduler (which was maintained by Alan Cox in his Linux 2.4-ac Kernel series) to the Linux 2.4 kernel used by the distribution.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In versions 2.6.0 to 2.6.22, the kernel used an O(1) scheduler developed by Ingo Molnar and many other kernel developers during the Linux 2.5 development.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] For many kernels in this time frame, Con Kolivas developed patch sets which improved interactivity with this scheduler or even replaced it with his own schedulers.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Con Kolivas' work, most significantly his implementation of fair scheduling named Rotating Staircase Deadline (RSDL), inspired Ingo Molnár to develop the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) as a replacement for the earlier O(1) scheduler, crediting Kolivas in his announcement.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] CFS is the first implementation of a fair queuing process scheduler widely used in a general-purpose operating system.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The CFS uses a well-studied, classic scheduling algorithm called fair queuing originally invented for packet networks.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Fair queuing had been previously applied to CPU scheduling under the name stride scheduling.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The fair queuing CFS scheduler has a scheduling complexity of $O(\log N)$ , where N is the number of tasks in the runqueue.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Choosing a task can be done in constant time, but reinserting a task after it has run requires $O(\log N)$ operations, because the run queue is implemented as a red–black tree.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The Brain Fuck Scheduler, also created by Con Kolivas, is an alternative to the CFS.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) process scheduler.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The aim was to remove the need for CFS *latency nice* patches.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Linux 6.12 added support for scheduler extensions that can be added from userspace; this mechanism is known as sched_ext.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] An eBPF program can be loaded into the kernel to implement a scheduling policy.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] These schedulers can replace the default scheduler.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] FreeBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–255.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for interrupts, 64–127 for the top half of the kernel, 128–159 for real-time user threads, 160–223 for time-shared user threads, and 224–255 for idle user threads.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Also, like Linux, it uses the active queue setup, but it also has an idle queue.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] NetBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–223.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for time-shared threads (default, SCHED_OTHER policy), 64–95 for user threads that entered kernel space, 96–128 for kernel threads, 128–191 for user real-time threads (SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR policies), and 192–223 for software interrupts.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Solaris uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging between 0 and 169.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Priorities 0–59 are reserved for time-shared threads, 60–99 for system threads, 100–159 for real-time threads, and 160–169 for low priority interrupts.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Unlike Linux, when a process is done using its time quantum, it is given a new priority and put back in the queue.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] Solaris 9 introduced two new scheduling classes, namely fixed-priority class and fair share class.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The threads with fixed priority have the same priority range as that of the time-sharing class, but their priorities are not dynamically adjusted.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] The fair scheduling class uses CPU *shares* to prioritize threads for scheduling decisions.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] CPU shares indicate the entitlement to CPU resources.
[src:apscheduler/scheduling-computing] They are allocated to a set of processes, which are collectively known as a project.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] A **time zone** is an area which observes a uniform standard time for legal, commercial, and social purposes.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Time zones tend to follow the boundaries between countries and their subdivisions instead of strictly following longitude, because it is convenient for areas in frequent communication to keep the same time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Each time zone is defined by a standard offset from Coordinated Universal Time (UTC).
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The offsets range from UTC−12:00 to UTC+14:00, and are usually a whole number of hours, but a few zones are offset by an additional 30 or 45 minutes, such as in India and Nepal.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Some areas in a time zone may use a different offset for part of the year, typically one hour ahead during spring and summer, a practice known as daylight saving time (DST).
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] In the table below, the locations that use daylight saving time are listed in their UTC offset when DST is *not* in effect.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] When DST is in effect, approximately during spring and summer, their UTC offset is increased by one hour (except for Lord Howe Island, where it is increased by 30 minutes).
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] For example, during the DST period, California observes UTC−07:00 and the United Kingdom observes UTC+01:00.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The apparent position of the Sun in the sky, and thus solar time, varies by location due to the spherical shape of the Earth.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] This variation corresponds to four minutes of time for every degree of longitude; for example, when it is solar noon in London, it is about 10 minutes before solar noon in Bristol, which is about 2.5 degrees to the west.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Local solar time has been associated with civil timekeeping since the development of sundials; for example, c.1500 BC, an ancient Egyptian sundial was used to measure laborers' work hours.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] In the 2nd century BC, Hipparchus developed a method to measure longitudinal distances by comparing local solar times when a lunar eclipse was simultaneously observed at two locations.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The work of Hipparchus is lost, but is known from citations in Strabo's Geographica, c.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The Royal Observatory, Greenwich, founded in 1675, established Greenwich Mean Time (GMT), the mean solar time at that location, as an aid to mariners to determine longitude at sea, providing a standard reference time while each location in England kept a different time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] In the 19th century, as transportation and telecommunications improved, it became increasingly inconvenient for each location to observe its own solar time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] In November 1840, the British Great Western Railway started using GMT kept by portable chronometers.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] This practice was soon adopted by other British railway companies and became known as **railway time**.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Around August 23, 1852, time signals were first transmitted by telegraph from the Royal Observatory.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] By 1855, 98% of Great Britain's public clocks were using GMT, but it was not made the island's legal time until August 2, 1880.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Some British clocks from this period have two minute hands, one for the local time and one for GMT.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] On November 2, 1868, the British Colony of New Zealand officially adopted a standard time to be observed throughout the colony.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] It was based on longitude 172°30′ east of Greenwich, or 11 hours 30 minutes ahead of GMT.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] This standard was known as New Zealand Mean Time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Timekeeping on North American railroads in the 19th century was complex.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Each railroad used its own standard time, usually based on the local time of its headquarters or most important terminus, and the railroad's train schedules were published using its own time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Some junctions served by several railroads had a clock for each railroad, each showing a different time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Because of this, a number of accidents occurred when trains from different companies using the same tracks mistimed their passings.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Dowd proposed a system of hourly standard time zones for North American railroads, although he published nothing on the matter at that time and did not consult railroad officials until 1869.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] In 1870, he proposed four ideal time zones having north–south borders, the first centered on Washington, D.C..
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] By 1872, the first was centered on the meridian 75° west of Greenwich, with natural borders such as sections of the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Dowd's system was never accepted by North American railroads.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Cleveland Abbe, chief meteorologist at the United States Weather Bureau, divided the United States into four standard time zones for consistency among the weather stations.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] In 1879, he published a paper titled *Report on Standard Time*.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] In 1883, he convinced North American railroad companies to adopt his time-zone system.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] In 1884, Britain, which had already adopted its own standard time system for England, Scotland, and Wales, helped gather international consent for global time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] In time, the American government, influenced in part by Abbe's 1879 paper, adopted the time-zone system.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Allen, the editor of the *Traveler's Official Railway Guide*.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The borders of its time zones ran through railroad stations, often in major cities.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] For example, the border between its Eastern and Central time zones ran through Detroit, Buffalo, Pittsburgh, Atlanta, and Charleston.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] It was inaugurated on Sunday, November 18, 1883, also called "The Day of Two Noons", when each railroad station clock was reset as standard-time noon was reached within each time zone.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The North American zones were named Intercolonial, Eastern, Central, Mountain, and Pacific.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Within a year 85% of all cities with populations over 10,000 (about 200 cities) were using standard time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The confusion of times came to an end when standard time zones were formally adopted by the U.S.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Congress in the Standard Time Act of March 19, 1918.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Italian mathematician Quirico Filopanti introduced the idea of a worldwide system of time zones in his book *Miranda!*, published in 1858.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] He proposed 24 hourly time zones, which he called "longitudinal days", the first centred on the meridian of Rome.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] He also proposed a universal time to be used in astronomy and telegraphy.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] However, his book attracted no attention until long after his death.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Scottish-born Canadian Sir Sandford Fleming proposed a worldwide system of time zones in 1876 - see Sandford Fleming § Inventor of worldwide standard time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The proposal divided the world into twenty-four time zones labeled A-Y (skipping J), each one covering 15 degrees of longitude.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] All clocks within each zone would be set to the same time as the others, but differed by one hour from those in the neighboring zones.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] He advocated his system at several international conferences, including the International Meridian Conference, where it received some consideration.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The system has not been directly adopted, but some maps divide the world into 24 time zones and assign letters to them, similarly to Fleming's system.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] By about 1900, almost all inhabited places on Earth had adopted a standard time zone, but only some of them used an hourly offset from GMT.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Many applied the time at a local astronomical observatory to an entire country, without any reference to GMT.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] It took many decades before all time zones were based on some standard offset from GMT or Coordinated Universal Time (UTC).
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] By 1929, the majority of countries had adopted hourly time zones, though some countries such as Iran, India, Myanmar, and parts of Australia had time zones with a 30-minute offset.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Nepal was the last country to adopt a standard offset, shifting slightly to UTC+05:45 in 1986.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] All nations currently use standard time zones for secular purposes, but not all of them apply the concept as originally conceived.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Several countries and subdivisions use half-hour or quarter-hour deviations from standard time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The consequences, in some areas, can affect the lives of local citizens, and in extreme cases contribute to larger political issues, such as in the western reaches of China.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] ISO 8601 is a standard established by the International Organization for Standardization defining methods of representing dates and times in textual form, including specifications for representing time zones.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] If a time is in UTC, a "Z" is added directly after the time without a separating space.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] "Z" is the zone designator for the zero UTC offset.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] UTC time is also known as "Zulu" time, since "Zulu" is a phonetic alphabet code word for the letter "Z".
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Offsets from UTC are written in the format ±hh:mm, ±hhmm, or ±hh (either hours ahead or behind UTC).
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] For example, if the time being described is one hour ahead of UTC (such as the time in Germany during the winter), the zone designator would be "+01:00", "+0100", or simply "+01".
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] This numeric representation of time zones is appended to local times in the same way that alphabetic time zone abbreviations (or "Z", as above) are appended.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The offset from UTC changes with daylight saving time, e.g. a time offset in Chicago, which is in the North American Central Time Zone, is "−06:00" for the winter (Central Standard Time) and "−05:00" for the summer (Central Daylight Time).
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Time zones are often represented by alphabetic abbreviations such as "EST", "WST", and "CST", though these are not part of the international time and date standard ISO 8601.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Such designations can be ambiguous; for example, "CST" can mean (North American) Central Standard Time (UTC−06:00), Cuba Standard Time (UTC−05:00), or China Standard Time (UTC+08:00), and is also a widely used variant of ACST (Australian Central Standard Time, UTC+09:30).
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] in which each side of the equation is equivalent to UTC.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] "time in zone B" = "time in zone A" − "UTC offset for zone A" + "UTC offset for zone B".
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] For example, the New York Stock Exchange opens at 09:30 (EST, UTC offset= −05:00).
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] These calculations become more complicated near the time switch to or from daylight saving time, as the UTC offset for the area becomes a function of UTC time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The time differences may also result in different dates.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] For example, when it is 22:00 on Monday in Egypt (UTC+02:00), it is 01:00 on Tuesday in Pakistan (UTC+05:00).
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The table "Time of day by zone" gives an overview on the time relations between different zones.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Since the 1920s, a nautical standard time system has been in operation for ships on the high seas.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] As an ideal form of the terrestrial time zone system, nautical time zones consist of gores of 15° offset from GMT by a whole number of hours.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] A nautical date line follows the 180th meridian, bisecting one 15° gore into two 7.5° gores that differ from GMT by ±12 hours.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] However, in practice each ship may choose what time to observe at each location.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Ships may decide to adjust their clocks at a convenient time, usually at night, not exactly when they cross a certain longitude.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Some ships simply remain on the time of the departing port during the whole trip.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Ideal time zones, such as nautical time zones, are based on the mean solar time of a particular meridian in the middle of that zone with boundaries located 7.5 degrees east and west of the meridian.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] In practice, however, many time zone boundaries are drawn much farther to the west, and some countries are located entirely outside their ideal time zones.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] For example, even though the Prime Meridian (0°) passes through Spain and France they use the mean solar time of 15 degrees east (Central European Time) rather than 0 degrees (Greenwich Mean Time).
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] France previously used GMT, but was switched to CET (Central European Time) during the German occupation of the country during World War II and did not switch back after the war.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Similarly, prior to World War II, the Netherlands observed "Amsterdam Time", which was twenty minutes ahead of Greenwich Mean Time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] They were obliged to follow German time during the war, and kept it thereafter.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] In the mid-1970s the Netherlands, as other European states, began observing daylight saving (summer) time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] One reason to draw time zone boundaries far to the west of their ideal meridians is to allow the more efficient use of afternoon sunlight.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Some of these locations also use daylight saving time, further increasing the difference to local solar time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] As a result, in summer, solar noon in the Spanish city of Vigo occurs at 14:41 clock time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] This westernmost area of continental Spain never experiences sunset before 18:00 clock time, even in winter, despite lying 42 degrees north of the equator.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Near the summer solstice, Vigo has sunset times after 22:00, similar to those of Stockholm, which is in the same time zone and 17 degrees farther north.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Stockholm has much earlier sunrises, though.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] In the United States, the reasons were more historical and business-related.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] In Midwestern states, like Indiana and Michigan, those living in Indianapolis and Detroit wanted to be on the same time zone as New York City to simplify communications and transactions.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] A more extreme example is Nome, Alaska, which is at 165°24′W longitude – just west of center of the idealized Samoa Time Zone (165°W).
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Nevertheless, Nome observes Alaska Time (135°W) with DST so it is slightly more than two hours ahead of the sun in winter and over three in summer.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Kotzebue, Alaska, also near the same meridian but north of the Arctic Circle, has *two* sunsets on the same day in early August, one shortly after midnight at the start of the day, and the other shortly before midnight at the end of the day.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Consequently, in early May, in Kotzebue one day does not have sunset.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] China extends as far west as 73°E, but all parts of it use UTC+08:00 (120°E), so solar "noon" can occur as late as 15:00 in western portions of China such as Xinjiang.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The Afghanistan-China border marks the greatest terrestrial time zone difference on Earth, with a 3.5 hour difference between Afghanistan's UTC+4:30 and China's UTC+08:00.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] A visualization of the mismatch between clock time and solar time in different locations.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] In blue areas, clock time lags behind solar time; in red areas, the reverse is true.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The two are synchronized in the white areas.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Many countries, and sometimes just certain regions of countries, adopt daylight saving time (DST), also known as summer time, during part of the year.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] This typically involves advancing clocks by an hour near the start of spring and adjusting back in autumn ("spring forward", "fall back").
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Modern DST was first proposed in 1907 and was in widespread use in 1916 as a wartime measure aimed at conserving coal.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Despite controversy, many countries have used it off and on since then; details vary by location and change occasionally.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Countries around the equator usually do not observe daylight saving time, since the seasonal difference in sunlight there is minimal.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Many computer operating systems include the necessary support for working with many or all possible local times.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Internally, operating systems typically use UTC as their basic time-keeping standard and convert local times, including daylight savings time, to and from UTC.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Web servers presenting web pages primarily for an audience in a single time zone or a limited range of time zones typically show times as a local time, perhaps with UTC time in brackets.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] More internationally oriented websites may show times in UTC only or using an arbitrary time zone.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] For example, the international English-language version of CNN includes GMT and Hong Kong Time, whereas the US version shows Eastern Time.US Eastern Time and Pacific Time are also used fairly commonly on many US-based English-language websites with global readership.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The format is typically based in the W3C Note "datetime".
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Email systems and other messaging systems (IRC chat, etc.) time-stamp messages using UTC, or else include the sender's time zone as part of the message, allowing the receiving program to display the message's date and time of sending in the recipient's local time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Database records that include a time stamp typically use UTC, especially when the database is part of a system that spans multiple time zones.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The use of local time for time-stamping records is not recommended for time zones that implement daylight saving time because once a year there is a one-hour period when local times are ambiguous.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Calendar systems nowadays usually tie their time stamps to UTC, and show them differently on computers that are in different time zones.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] That works when having telephone or internet meetings.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] It works less well when travelling, because the calendar events are assumed to take place in the time zone the computer or smartphone was on when creating the event.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The event can be shown at the wrong time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] For example, if a Los Angeles resident visits New York and before the journey makes a calendar entry for the return flight at 9 am (which the computer assumes is Los Angeles time), the calendar entry will be at noon if taking the computer's new New York time zone.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Calendaring software must also deal with daylight saving time (DST), usually done so calendar entries made before the shift are shown the same after it.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] If, for political reasons, the begin and end dates of daylight saving time are changed, calendar entries should stay the same in local time, even though they may shift in UTC time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Unix-like systems, including Linux and macOS, keep system time in Unix time format, representing the number of seconds that have elapsed since 00:00:00 Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) on Thursday, January 1, 1970, excluding leap seconds.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Unix time is usually converted to local time when displayed to the user, and times specified by the user in local time are converted to Unix time.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The conversion takes into account the time zone and daylight saving time rules; by default the time zone and daylight saving time rules are set up when the system is configured, though individual processes can specify time zones and daylight saving time rules using the *TZ* environment variable.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] This allows users in multiple time zones, or in the same time zone but with different daylight saving time rules, to use the same computer, with their respective local times displayed correctly to each user.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Information about time zones and daylight saving time rules most commonly comes from the IANA time zone database.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Many systems, including anything using the GNU C Library, a C library based on the BSD C library, or the System V Release 4 C library, can make use of the IANA time zone database.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Windows-based computer systems prior to Windows 95 and Windows NT used local time, but Windows 95 and later, and Windows NT, base system time on UTC.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] They allow a program to fetch the system time as UTC, represented as a year, month, day, hour, minute, second, and millisecond; Windows 95 and later, and Windows NT 3.5 and later, also allow the system time to be fetched as a count of 100 ns units since 1601-01-01 00:00:00 UTC.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The system registry contains time zone information that includes the offset from UTC and rules that indicate the start and end dates for daylight saving in each zone.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Interaction with the user normally uses local time, and application software is able to calculate the time in various zones.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Terminal Servers allow remote computers to redirect their time zone settings to the Terminal Server so that users see the correct time for their time zone in their desktop/application sessions.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Terminal Services uses the server base time on the Terminal Server and the client time zone information to calculate the time in the session.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] While most application software will use the underlying operating system for time zone and daylight saving time rule information, the Java Platform, from version 1.3.1, has maintained its own database of time zone and daylight saving time rule information, based on the IANA time zone database.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] This database is updated whenever time zone or daylight saving time rules change.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Oracle provides an updater tool for this purpose.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] As an alternative to the information bundled with the Java Platform, programmers may choose to use the Joda-Time library.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] This library includes its own data based on the IANA time zone database.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] As of Java 8 there is a new date and time API that can help with converting times.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Traditionally, there was very little in the way of time zone support for JavaScript.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Essentially the programmer had to extract the UTC offset by instantiating a time object, getting a GMT time from it, and differencing the two.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] This does not provide a solution for more complex daylight saving variations, such as divergent DST directions between northern and southern hemispheres.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] ECMA-402, the standard on Internationalization API for JavaScript, provides ways of formatting Time Zones.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] However, due to size constraint, some implementations or distributions do not include it.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The DateTime object in Perl supports all entries in the IANA time zone database and includes the ability to get, set and convert between time zones.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The DateTime objects and related functions have been compiled into the PHP core since 5.2.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] This includes the ability to get and set the default script time zone, and DateTime is aware of its own time zone internally.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] PHP.net provides extensive documentation on this.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] As noted there, the most current time zone database can be implemented via the PECL timezonedb.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The standard module datetime included with Python stores and operates on the time zone information class tzinfo.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The third party pytz module provides access to the full IANA time zone database.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Negated time zone offset in seconds is stored time.timezone and time.altzone attributes.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] From Python 3.9, the zoneinfo module introduces timezone management without need for third party module.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Each Smalltalk dialect comes with its own built-in classes for dates, times and timestamps, only a few of which implement the DateAndTime and Duration classes as specified by the ANSI Smalltalk Standard.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] VisualWorks provides a TimeZone class that supports up to two annually recurring offset transitions, which are assumed to apply to all years (same behavior as Windows time zones).
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Squeak provides a Timezone class that does not support any offset transitions.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Dolphin Smalltalk does not support time zones at all.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Orbiting spacecraft may experience many sunrises and sunsets, or none, in a 24-hour period.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Therefore, it is not possible to calibrate the time with respect to the Sun and still respect a 24-hour sleep/wake cycle.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] A common practice for space exploration is to use the Earth-based time of the launch site or mission control, synchronizing the sleeping cycles of the crew and controllers.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] The International Space Station normally uses Coordinated Universal Time (UTC).
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Timekeeping on Mars can be more complex, since the planet has a solar day of approximately 24 hours and 40 minutes, known as a sol.
[src:apscheduler/time-zone] Earth controllers for some Mars missions have synchronized their sleep/wake cycles with the Martian day, when specifically solar-powered rover activity occurs.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] If you don’t have pip installed, you can easily install it by downloading and running get-pip.py.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] The source distribution contains the `examples` directory where you can find many working examples for using APScheduler in different ways.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] The examples can also be browsed online.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] Your choice of scheduler depends mostly on your programming environment and what you’ll be using APScheduler for.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] To pick the appropriate job store, you need to determine whether you need job persistence or not.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] If you always recreate your jobs at the start of your application, then you can probably go with the default (`MemoryJobStore`).
[src:apscheduler/userguide] But if you need your jobs to persist over scheduler restarts or application crashes, then your choice usually boils down to what tools are used in your programming environment.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] If, however, you are in the position to choose freely, then `SQLAlchemyJobStore` on a PostgreSQL backend is the recommended choice due to its strong data integrity protection.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] Likewise, the choice of executors is usually made for you if you use one of the frameworks above.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] Otherwise, the default `ThreadPoolExecutor` should be good enough for most purposes.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] If your workload involves CPU intensive operations, you should consider using `ProcessPoolExecutor` instead to make use of multiple CPU cores.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] You could even use both at once, adding the process pool executor as a secondary executor.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] When you schedule a job, you need to choose a *trigger* for it.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] The trigger determines the logic by which the dates/times are calculated when the job will be run.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] It is also possible to combine multiple triggers into one which fires either on times agreed on by all the participating triggers, or when any of the triggers would fire.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] For more information, see the documentation for `combining triggers`.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] You can find the plugin names of each job store, executor and trigger type on their respective API documentation pages.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] APScheduler provides many different ways to configure the scheduler.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] You can use a configuration dictionary or you can pass in the options as keyword arguments.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] You can also instantiate the scheduler first, add jobs and configure the scheduler afterwards.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] This way you get maximum flexibility for any environment.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] The full list of scheduler level configuration options can be found on the API reference of the `BaseScheduler` class.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] Scheduler subclasses may also have additional options which are documented on their respective API references.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] Configuration options for individual job stores and executors can likewise be found on their API reference pages.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] This will get you a BackgroundScheduler with a MemoryJobStore named “default” and a ThreadPoolExecutor named “default” with a default maximum thread count of 10.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] You want to have *two* job stores using *two* executors and you also want to tweak the default values for new jobs and set a different timezone.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] Starting the scheduler is done by simply calling `start()` on the scheduler.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] For schedulers other than `BlockingScheduler`, this call will return immediately and you can continue the initialization process of your application, possibly adding jobs to the scheduler.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] For BlockingScheduler, you will only want to call `start()` after you’re done with any initialization steps.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] After the scheduler has been started, you can no longer alter its settings.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] The first way is the most common way to do it.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] The second way is mostly a convenience to declare jobs that don’t change during the application’s run time.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] The `add_job()` method returns a `apscheduler.job.Job` instance that you can use to modify or remove the job later.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] You can schedule jobs on the scheduler **at any time**.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] If the scheduler is not yet running when the job is added, the job will be scheduled *tentatively* and its first run time will only be computed when the scheduler starts.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] Of the builtin job stores, only MemoryJobStore doesn’t serialize jobs.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] Of the builtin executors, only ProcessPoolExecutor will serialize jobs.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] If you schedule jobs in a persistent job store during your application’s initialization, you **MUST** define an explicit ID for the job and use `replace_existing=True` or you will get a new copy of the job every time your application restarts!
[src:apscheduler/userguide] To run a job immediately, omit `trigger` argument when adding the job.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] When you remove a job from the scheduler, it is removed from its associated job store and will not be executed anymore.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] The latter method is probably more convenient, but it requires that you store somewhere the `Job` instance you received when adding the job.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] For jobs scheduled via the `scheduled_job()`, the first way is the only way.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] If the job’s schedule ends (i.e. its trigger doesn’t produce any further run times), it is automatically removed.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] You can easily pause and resume jobs through either the `Job` instance or the scheduler itself.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] When a job is paused, its next run time is cleared and no further run times will be calculated for it until the job is resumed.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] To get a machine processable list of the scheduled jobs, you can use the `get_jobs()` method.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] It will return a list of `Job` instances.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] If you’re only interested in the jobs contained in a particular job store, then give a job store alias as the second argument.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] As a convenience, you can use the `print_jobs()` method which will print out a formatted list of jobs, their triggers and next run times.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] You can modify any job attributes by calling either `apscheduler.job.Job.modify()` or `modify_job()`.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] You can modify any Job attributes except for `id`.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] If you want to reschedule the job – that is, change its trigger, you can use either `apscheduler.job.Job.reschedule()` or `reschedule_job()`.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] These methods construct a new trigger for the job and recalculate its next run time based on the new trigger.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] By default, the scheduler shuts down its job stores and executors and waits until all currently executing jobs are finished.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] This will still shut down the job stores and executors but does not wait for any running tasks to complete.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] This is useful when you need to prune unwanted jobs before they have a chance to run.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] By default, only one instance of each job is allowed to be run at the same time.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] This means that if the job is about to be run but the previous run hasn’t finished yet, then the latest run is considered a misfire.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] It is possible to set the maximum number of instances for a particular job that the scheduler will let run concurrently, by using the `max_instances` keyword argument when adding the job.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] Sometimes the scheduler may be unable to execute a scheduled job at the time it was scheduled to run.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] The most common case is when a job is scheduled in a persistent job store and the scheduler is shut down and restarted after the job was supposed to execute.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] When this happens, the job is considered to have “misfired”.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] The scheduler will then check each missed execution time against the job’s `misfire_grace_time` option (which can be set on per-job basis or globally in the scheduler) to see if the execution should still be triggered.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] This can lead into the job being executed several times in succession.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] If this behavior is undesirable for your particular use case, it is possible to use `coalescing` to roll all these missed executions into one.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] In other words, if coalescing is enabled for the job and the scheduler sees one or more queued executions for the job, it will only trigger it once.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] No misfire events will be sent for the “bypassed” runs.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] If the execution of a job is delayed due to no threads or processes being available in the pool, the executor may skip it due to it being run too late (compared to its originally designated run time).
[src:apscheduler/userguide] If this is likely to happen in your application, you may want to either increase the number of threads/processes in the executor, or adjust the `misfire_grace_time` setting to a higher value.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] It is possible to attach event listeners to the scheduler.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] Scheduler events are fired on certain occasions, and may carry additional information in them concerning the details of that particular event.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] It is possible to listen to only particular types of events by giving the appropriate `mask` argument to `add_listener()`, OR’ing the different constants together.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] The listener callable is called with one argument, the event object.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] See the documentation for the `events` module for specifics on the available events and their attributes.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] If you need to migrate your jobs to a different job store, you need to first export the jobs to a JSON document and then import them back again.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] Both methods take a `jobstore` argument which can limit the source job store (on export), or specify a non-default target job store (on import).
[src:apscheduler/userguide] The first argument for both methods can either be an open file, a `Path` or a file system path as a string.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] If the scheduler isn’t working as expected, it will be helpful to increase the logging level of the `apscheduler` logger to the `DEBUG` level.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] This should provide lots of useful information about what’s going on inside the scheduler.
[src:apscheduler/userguide] Also make sure that you check the Frequently Asked Questions section to see if your problem already has a solution.
